'''Rally Championship''' is a series of loosely related [[rallying|rally]] [[video games]], focused on [[rally racing]] and based on what is now known as the [[Rally GB]]. The series began in 1988 with Europress' ''Lombard RAC Rally'' game and ended in 2002. Each game in the series had many different front covers.
==''Lombard RAC Rally'' (1988) == {{anchor|lombardracrally}} {{main|Lombard RAC Rally (video game)}} In 1988, Europress released ''Lombard RAC Rally'' for the [[Atari ST]]<ref>http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-st-lombard-rac-rally_22603.html</ref> and [[Amiga]]<ref>http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=1581</ref> under their [[Mandarin Software]] label. This was based on the same rally (under the earlier sponsors' names) as the later ''Network Q RAC Rally'' games.
The game prominently featured an animated driver, seen from behind moving the steering wheel, with the road seen through the car's windscreen.
==''Network Q RAC Rally'' (1993)== {{Main|Network Q RAC Rally (video game)}}
Five years after ''Lombard RAC Rally'', in 1993 Europress released '''[[Network Q RAC Rally (video game)|Network Q RAC Rally]]''' for [[MS-DOS]].
==''Network Q RAC Rally Championship'' (1996)== {{Main|Network Q RAC Rally Championship (1996)}}
The next game in the series was called '''[[Network Q RAC Rally Championship]]'''. It was released for [[MS-DOS]] and [[Windows]] in 1996. This new version has more tracks, cars, and better graphics.
A 1997 version also came, which included a ''X-Miles add-on'' and some newer features. This version was published by Actualize instead of [[Europress]].
==''International Rally Championship'' (1997)== {{Main|International Rally Championship}}
'''[[International Rally Championship]]''' came in November 1997, and became available for [[Windows]] and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]. New features arrived, such as Track Editor and playable up to 8 players via [[LAN]].
==''Mobil 1 Rally Championship'' (1999)== {{Main|Mobil 1 Rally Championship}}
'''[[Mobil 1 Rally Championship]]''' came in December 1999, for [[Windows]] and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]. The Windows version of the game has been viewed as one of the most realistic game, due to very high quality graphics for its time, unlike the unsuccessful PlayStation version.
==''Rally Championship Xtreme'' (2001)== {{Main|Rally Championship Xtreme}}
'''[[Rally Championship Xtreme]]''' came in November 2001 for [[Windows]]. It was not really as successful as its predecessor.
==''Rally Championship'' (2002)== {{Main|Rally Championship (video game)}}
The sixth game of the series was called '''[[Rally Championship (video game)|Rally Championship]]'''. It was released for [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Nintendo GameCube]] in May 2002. It was the last of the series.
