{{Infobox Film Festival | name = Toronto Jewish Film Festival (TJFF) | image =File:Toronto_Jewish_Film_Festival_logo.gif | caption = | location = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] | awards = | founded = 1993 | host = | number = | language = International | website = http://tjff.com/ }}
The '''Toronto Jewish Film Festival''' (TJFF) is an annual [[film festival]] held in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada. It is described as the largest Jewish film festival in the world.<ref name="UJA">{{cite web | url=http://www.jewishtorontoonline.net/home.do?ch=events&cid=org-1329&jt_style=detail | title=Toronto Jewish Film Festival | publisher=UJA Federation | work=Doing Jewish in Toronto | date=2014 | accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref>
The Festival was founded in 1993.
The 2014 Festival ran from May 1 to May 11<ref name="2014 PR">{{cite press release | url=http://tjff.com/info.php?pid=13 | title=A World Of Great Filmmaking Comes to Town | publisher=Toronto Jewish Film Festival | date=April 10, 2014 | accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Glassman">{{cite news | url=http://povmagazine.com/blog/view/toronto-jewish-film-festival-2014 | title=Toronto Jewish Film Festival 2014 | work=Point of View magazine | date=May 7, 2014 | accessdate=September 1, 2014 | author=Marc Glassman | location=Toronto}}</ref> and featured 116 films from 23 countries.<ref name="Glassman"/>
